<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,312,1218]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Posterior tip of sternohyoideus 18.7%, overlapping heart by 0.07 snout-heart gap, heart 4.3% (MP = 19.7%), snout-heart interval 21.8%, heart-liver gap 7.0%, liver lobes multipartite, right liver 47.5% (MP = 52.6%) with 41.0 (33–47) segments, left liver 46.0% (MP = 50.8%) with 34.3 (32–36) segments, anterior (left) liver extension –0.02, posterior liver tail 0.05, left liver = 0.97 right liver, liver-gall bladder overlap 2.1%, gall bladder 1.2% (MP = 74.9%) wedged between a caudal, transversely oriented pancreas (2.0%) and a small cranial juxtasplenic body (1.0%) and spleen (1.0%), pancreas lacking splenic limb, right ovary 3.6% (MP = 82.5%) with 1.7 (1–2) ova and 7.3 (4–9) follicles, left ovary 3.9% (MP = 85.1%) with 2.0 (1–3) ova and 4.3 (3–5) follicles, right adrenal MP = 83.5%, left adrenal MP = 85.4%, kidneys smooth, segmented and compact, individual segments also with creases, right kidney 4.4% (MP = 87.4%) with 5.0 (4–6) segments, left kidney 4.8% (MP = 89.7%) with 4.3 (4–5) segments, kidney-vent interval 14.9%, kidney-vent gap 7.8%, kidney overlap 0.32, rectal caecum 2.0%, bulbous and 2–3 times the diameter of adjacent small intestine, caecum-vent interval 9.8%.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,312,1218]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Respiratory system lacking tracheal lung and left lung complex, trachea 20.5% (MP = 11.6%), estimated number of tracheal rings 139.3 (126–152) or 66.5 rings/10% SVL, anterior lung tip 20.0%, tracheal entry paraterminal with “anterior lobe” that is fused to trachea and lacking a lumen, cardiac lung 1.9% with several large faveoli but lacking anterior pocket, right lung 39.3% (MP = 41.5%), broad throughout its length, cranial 0.15–0.35 with 2–3 layers of rounded faveoli, caudal 0.65–0.85 reticulate with network of trabeculae, posterior tip 61.2%, bronchus 17.1%, posterior tip of bronchus 38.9%, bronchus = 0.45 right lung, trachea-bronchus 37.6% (MP = 20.1%), total lung 41.2% (MP = 40.6%).</paragraph>
